                "slug": "oblique-pen-holder",
                "isOptional": true
              },
              {
                "name": "Cartridge paper, 130 gsm (practice sheets)",
                "slug": "cartridge-paper-130",
                "isOptional": false
              },
              {
                "name": "Iron-gall ink (modern formulation)",
                "slug": "iron-gall-ink",
                "isOptional": false
              },
              {
                "name": "Metal ruler, 30 cm",
                "slug": "metal-ruler-30cm",
                "isOptional": false
              },
              {
                "name": "Tracing paper (as hand guard under writing hand)",
                "slug": "tracing-paper",
                "isOptional": false
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Broad-edge warm-up (Mitchell or Brause nib)",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Charge the nib and draw five straight downstrokes from x-height to baseline, holding the nib at the target angle (30 degrees for Foundational; 45 degrees for Italic or Fraktur). Space them evenly. Look for consistent width: all five should be the same weight.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Draw five branching strokes: start at the baseline, pull upward to x-height, and arc right to end at the hairline. This is the arch preparation for letters like n, m, and h.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Draw five ovals without lifting the pen. The oval is anticlockwise: start at 1 o'clock, arc left and downward to the base, continue right and upward, and close at 1 o'clock. If the closing point is above or below the starting point, the oval is not closed and the letterforms will be open.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Write the letter n five times. After the warm-up strokes, the first n should already show more consistent weight and angle than a cold-start n.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Pointed-pen warm-up (Nikko G or Hunt 101)",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Draw ten oval shapes (anticlockwise) with no pressure, keeping the line a hairline throughout. These establish a consistent stroke path before pressure is added.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Repeat the oval exercise, this time applying pressure on the left downstroke and releasing to a hairline on the upstroke. The shade should build from the top of the left curve to the base, then release smoothly.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Draw ten underturn strokes: pull from x-height to baseline with a shaded downstroke, then turn right and ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "push",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpqsiohg0000esv4vg4ydo0c"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " upward as a hairline to x-height. This is the basic Copperplate minuscule stroke used in u, n, and m.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "After warm-up",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Once the warm-up strokes are complete, rule the guide lines for the work session and begin writing. The warm-up practice sheet does not need to be saved; it is a functional tool, not a finished piece. Some calligraphers keep a practice journal for warm-up sheets to track improvement across sessions, but the choice is entirely practical.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
